==English==

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|deh₃}}
Either from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|abscondre}} or directly from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abscondere}}, present active infinitive of {{m|la|abscondō||hide}}; formed from {{m|la|abs}}, {{m|la|ab||away}} + {{m|la|condō||put together, store}}, from {{m|la|con||together}} + {{m|la|dō||put}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=4}}</ref>.
* Cognate with {{m|en|sconce||a type of light fixture}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əbˈskɒnd/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈskɑnd/|/æbˈzkɑnd/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɒnd|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|intransitive|reflexive|archaic}} To [[hide]], to be in hiding or concealment.
#* {{quote-book|year=1691-1735|author={{w|John Ray}}|title=The Wisdom of God Manifested in the Works of the Creation|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rRI5AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA300&dq=intitle:works+of+creation+inauthor:ray&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mpnNUZHMJ4Pu0gGZo4GICw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=absconds&f=false|passage=<!--The work was in editions while Ray was alive from 1691 to 1705. Google Books has the citation only in a 1735 edition.-->the ''Marmotto'', {{...}} which '''absconds''' all Winter doth {{...}} live upon its own Fat.<!--MW 1913 has "the marmot absconds all winter"-->}}
# {{label|en|intransitive|reflexive}} To [[flee]], often [[secretly]]; to [[steal away]], particularly to avoid arrest or prosecution. {{defdate|From mid 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1848|author={{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}|title=[[w:The History of England from the Accession of James the Second|The History of England]]|chapter=13|passage={{...}} that very homesickness which, in regular armies, drives so many recruits to '''abscond''' at the risk of stripes and of death.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1911|author={{w|Ambrose Bierce}}|title={{w|The Devil's Dictionary}}|passage=Spring beckons! All things to the call respond;<br>The trees are leaving and cashiers '''abscond'''.}}
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To [[withdraw]] from. {{defdate|From mid 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref>
#* {{quote-book|year=2006|author=Richard Rojcewicz|title=The Gods And Technology: A Reading Of Heidegger|isbn=0791482308|passage=Modern technology accompanies the '''absconding''' of the original attitude.<!--What does this mean? It is a paraphrase of a translation of Heidegger.-->}}
#* {{quote-book|year=2009|author=Sonia Brill|title=Relationships Without Anger|isbn=144902789X|passage=You cannot '''abscond''' from the responsibility both you and your partner owe to this event, and that includes dealing with anger issues and any other emotional issues that come with it.}}
# {{label|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[conceal]]; to take away. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|title=treatise on the eye, the manner and phaenomena of vision|volume=2|author=William Porterfield|editor=G. Hamilton, John Balfour|year=1759|passage=for having applied to the Side of the Head any thin black Body, such as the Brim of a Hat, so as it may '''abscond''' the Objects that are upon that Side}}
#* {{quote-book|title=The Buccaneers of America|page=161|books.google.com/books?isbn=1108024815|author={{w|John Esquemeling}}, Henry Powell|year_published=2010|year=1684|passage=They examined every prisoner by himself (who were in all about two hundred and fifty persons) where they had '''absconded''' the rest of their goods}}
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[evade]], to [[hide]] or [[flee]] from.
#: {{ux|en|The captain '''absconded''' his responsibility.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=2006|author=Aldo E. Chircop, Olof Lindén|title=Places of Refuge for Ships|isbn=900414952X|passage=If the distress situation is solved succesfully, the anonymous shipowner will reap the commercial benefit, if the situation ends in disaster, the shipowner will hide behind an anonymous post box in a foreign country and will '''abscond''' responsibility.}}
#* {{quote-book|title=The Mystical Harvest|page=431|books.google.com/books?isbn=0595481140|author=Somar|year=2008|passage=The driver snatched a packet of cigarettes out of the glove compartment and '''absconded''' the driver's seat without a word}}
#* {{quote-book|title=Girls on the Verge: Debutante Dips, Drive-bys, and Other Initiations|page=29|books.google.com/books?isbn=1429981970|author=Vendela Vida|year=2007|passage=Those who evidently did not get invited back to their top choices have already '''absconded''' the scene, tripping in their high heels as they ran.}}
#* {{quote-book|title=Gangland Melbourne|page=47|books.google.com/books?isbn=0522858694|author=James Morton, Susanna Lobez|year=2011|passage=In 1939 she '''absconded''' her bail in Melbourne and went to New Zealand, where she also absconded on a charge of stealing diamonds.}}

